Q1. Visualizing patient trajectory

Visualizing a patientâs encounters in a health care system is a common task in clinical data analysis. In this question, we will visualize a patientâs ADT (admission-discharge-transfer) history and ICU vitals in the MIMIC-IV data.

Q1.1 ADT history

A patientâs ADT history records the time of admission, discharge, and transfer in the hospital. This figure shows the ADT history of the patient with subject_id 10001217 in the MIMIC-IV data. The x-axis is the calendar time, and the y-axis is the type of event (ADT, lab, procedure). The color of the line segment represents the care unit. The size of the line segment represents whether the care unit is an ICU/CCU. The crosses represent lab events, and the shape of the dots represents the type of procedure. The title of the figure shows the patientâs demographic information and the subtitle shows top 3 diagnoses.

Do a similar visualization for the patient with subject_id 10013310 using ggplot.

Hint: We need to pull information from data files patients.csv.gz, admissions.csv.gz, transfers.csv.gz, labevents.csv.gz, procedures_icd.csv.gz, diagnoses_icd.csv.gz, d_icd_procedures.csv.gz, and d_icd_diagnoses.csv.gz. For the big file labevents.csv.gz, use the Parquet format you generated in Homework 2. For reproducibility, make the Parquet folder labevents_pq available at the current working directory hw3, for example, by a symbolic link. Make your code reproducible.

hadm_id_top3 <- diag_icd_1 %>%

transfers_1 <- transfers_1 %>%
  mutate(careunit_1 = case_when(
    careunit == "Emergency Department" ~ "Emergency Department",
    careunit == "Medicine/Cardiology" ~ "Medicine",
    careunit == "Neuro Intermediate" ~ "Neuro Intermediate",
    careunit == "Neuro Surgical Intensive Care Unit (Neuro SICU)" ~ "ICU",

    careunit == "Coronary Care Unit (CCU)" ~ "ICU"))

transfers_plot <- transfers_1 %>%
  mutate(event_category = 'ADT')

  mutate(event_category = 'Lab')

  mutate(event_category = 'Procedure')

  format = "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S")

final_plot <-
ggplot(combined_data) +
  geom_segment(data = subset(combined_data, event_category == 'ADT'), 
               aes(x = intime, xend = outtime, y = event_category, 
               yend = event_category, color = careunit_1, linewidth = is_icu)) +
  geom_point(data = subset(combined_data, event_category == 'Lab'),
             aes(x = charttime, y = event_category), shape = 3) +
  geom_point(data = subset(combined_data, event_category == 'Procedure'),
             aes(x = chartdate, y = event_category, shape = short_title)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Emergency Department" = "red", 
                              "Medicine" = "green", "Neuro Intermediate" = 
                                "blue", "ICU" = "purple")) +
  scale_size_manual(values = c(1, 5)) +

       subtitle = "STEMI involving right coronary artery
       acute kidney failure with tubular necrosis
       acute on chronic systolic (congestive) heart failure", 
       x = "Calendar Time", y = "") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme_light() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust=1, size = 8),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 7),

Q1.2 ICU stays

ICU stays are a subset of ADT history. This figure shows the vitals of the patient 10001217 during ICU stays. The x-axis is the calendar time, and the y-axis is the value of the vital. The color of the line represents the type of vital. The facet grid shows the abbreviation of the vital and the stay ID.

Do a similar visualization for the patient 10013310.

Answer: First, we need the data in the vitals for ICU patients, which is the exercise we did in hw2. Because in hw2, we only have the itemid for mean non-invasive blood pressure (220181), so I will use NBPm instead of NBPd.

cd  ~/mimic/icu
gzip -cd chartevents.csv.gz > ~/203b-lecture/203b-hw/hw3/chartevents.csv
item_ids_chart <- c(220045, 220181, 220179, 223761, 220210)
icu_vital_1.2 <- open_dataset("chartevents.csv", format = "csv") %>%
  select(subject_id, hadm_id, itemid, charttime, valuenum) %>%
  filter(itemid %in% item_ids_chart, subject_id == 10013310) %>%
  collect()
item_names <- data.frame(
  itemid = c(220045, 220181, 220179, 223761, 220210),
  item_name = c("HR", "NBPm", "NBPs", "Temperature", "RR"))

icu_vital_1.2 <- icu_vital_1.2 %>%
  left_join(item_names, by = "itemid")
ggplot(data = icu_vital_1.2, aes(x = charttime, y = valuenum, group = hadm_id, 
  color = item_name)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(item_name ~ hadm_id, scales = "free", space = "fixed") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Patient 10013310 ICU stays - Vitals", 
  x = "Calendar Time", 
  y = "Value") +
  theme_minimal() +  
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust=1, size = 8),
  axis.text.y = element_text(size = 7), 
  legend.position = "bottom")

Q2.2 Summary and visualization

How many unique subject_id? Can a subject_id have multiple ICU stays? Summarize the number of ICU stays per subject_id by graphs.

Answer: By running the code, we can tell that we have 50,920 unique subject_id, thus we do have some subject_id have multiple ICU stays since the original row number is 73,181.

unique_subject_id <- icustays_tble %>% distinct(subject_id)
nrow(unique_subject_id)
[1] 50920
icu_summary <- icustays_tble %>%
  group_by(subject_id) %>%
  summarise(icu_stays_num = n()) %>%
  count(icu_stays_num)

ggplot(icu_summary, aes(x = icu_stays_num, y = n)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Number of ICU Stays", y = "Number of Subjects", 
       title = "Distribution of ICU Stays per Subject") +
  xlim(0, 40)

Summarize the following information by graphics and explain any patterns you see.

  • number of admissions per patient Answer: We can tell that itâs a extremely skewed data.
admissions_per_patient <- admissions_tble %>%
  group_by(subject_id) %>%
  summarise(number_of_admissions = n()) %>%
  count(number_of_admissions)

ggplot(data = admissions_per_patient) +

Answer: The plot showed high frequency at 0, 15, 30 and 45 minutesï¼ possibly due to the rounding.

  • length of hospital stay (from admission to discharge) (anything unusual?)
admissions_tble <- admissions_tble %>%
  mutate("length_stay" = round(as.numeric(difftime(admissions_tble$dischtime,
                                  admissions_tble$admittime, 
                                  units = "days"))))


ggplot(admissions_tble) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes (x = length_stay))

  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Length of the Hospital Stay per Patient",
       x = "Length of Stay",
       y = "Count")

Answer: We have a lot of people with length of stay equals to 0 and -1, which is quite unusual, not sure what was happening.

According to the MIMIC-IV documentation,

All dates in the database have been shifted to protect patient confidentiality. Dates will be internally consistent for the same patient, but randomly distributed in the future. Dates of birth which occur in the present time are not true dates of birth. Furthermore, dates of birth which occur before the year 1900 occur if the patient is older than 89. In these cases, the patientâs age at their first admission has been fixed to 300.

Q4.2 Summary and visualization

Summarize variables gender and anchor_age by graphics, and explain any patterns you see.

Answer: The first graph is the histogram showing the distribution of gender, more females presented. The second boxplot showed the anchor distribution by gender. Both have a similar range, whereas males have a higher median anchor age compared to females.

ggplot(patients_tble) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = gender, fill = gender)) 

ggplot(data = patients_tble, mapping = aes(x = gender, 
                                           y = anchor_age)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + labs(title = "Anchor age by gender") +
  labs(x = "Gender", y = "Anchor age")

Answer: This graph also showed the anchor_age distribution by gender. We have a peak at age 91. Both gender have a similar trend.

ggplot(patients_tble) +
  geom_bar (aes(x = anchor_age, fill = gender)) + 
  labs(title = "Anchor age by gender")

Q7. Putting things together

Let us create a tibble mimic_icu_cohort for all ICU stays, where rows are all ICU stays of adults (age at intime >= 18) and columns contain at least following variables

  • all variables in icustays_tble
  • all variables in admissions_tble
  • all variables in patients_tble
  • the last lab measurements before the ICU stay in labevents_tble
  • the first vital measurements during the ICU stay in chartevents_tble

The final mimic_icu_cohort should have one row per ICU stay and columns for each variable.
